{"timestamp": "2026-07-11T02:09:26.248386+00:00", "level": "INFO", "logger": "llm_policy_library.agents.response", "message": "answer generated", "correlation_id": "0dffca79-ca41-4519-a5e9-841ed0523451", "query": "What controls apply to API security?", "citations": ["ia-9", "ia-13", "ia-13.2", "ac-20.1", "ia-5.2"], "answer_chars": 1721}
{"timestamp": "2026-07-11T02:09:26.299267+00:00", "level": "INFO", "logger": "llm_policy_library.orchestrator", "message": "query answered", "correlation_id": "0dffca79-ca41-4519-a5e9-841ed0523451", "query": "What controls apply to API security?", "answer": "Applicable controls for API security from the supplied list:\n\n- Authenticate service-to-service and application connections used by APIs: require unique identification and authentication of system services and applications before establishing communications (applies to API clients and backend services) [ia-9].\n\n- Use centralized identity/authorization infrastructure for API access control: employ identity providers and authorization servers to manage user, device, and non-person entity identities, attributes, and access rights used in authentication and authorization decisions for API calls, per organizational policy and configured mechanisms [ia-13].\n\n- Verify tokens/assertions presented to APIs: verify the source and integrity of identity assertions and access tokens before granting access to system and information resources via the API (e.g., validate signatures, issuer, audience, expiry) [ia-13.2].\n\n- Enforce limits and conditions on external API consumers/hosts: permit external systems to access or process organization-controlled information only after verifying required controls on the external system or retaining approved connection/processing agreements (useful for third-party APIs and integrations) [ac-20.1].\n\n- Where APIs use public key-based authentication (mutual TLS, client certs, signed requests), protect private keys, map authenticated identities to accounts, validate certificates to a trust anchor including revocation checking, and locally cache revocation data to support validation [ia-5.2].\n\nIf you want, I can map these controls to concrete API security measures (e.g., token validation steps, mutual TLS configuration, third-party onboarding checklist) \u2014 say which you prefer.", "latency_ms": 6426.9, "document_count": 5, "citations": ["ia-9", "ia-13", "ia-13.2", "ac-20.1", "ia-5.2"], "is_fallback": false}
