{"timestamp": "2026-07-11T02:09:32.349469+00:00", "level": "INFO", "logger": "llm_policy_library.orchestrator", "message": "query answered", "correlation_id": "7a90a0ea-81a0-4d80-b543-6d591360f910", "query": "What policies relate to logging and monitoring?", "answer": "Policies relating to logging and monitoring are covered by the supplied controls as follows:\n\n- Event logging: Define what event types the system can log, coordinate logging with other organizational entities, specify which event types will actually be logged and how often, document why those event types suffice for post\u2011incident investigations, and review/update the selected event types on a defined schedule [au-2].\n\n- Session-level capture: Provide capability for designated users/roles to record, view, hear, or log user session content under defined circumstances, and ensure session auditing is developed and used in consultation with legal counsel and applicable authorities [au-14].\n\n- Maintenance session logging and review: Require logging of organization\u2011defined audit events for nonlocal maintenance/diagnostic sessions and review those maintenance audit records to detect anomalous behavior [ma-4.1].\n\n- System monitoring for attacks and misuse: Monitor systems to detect attacks and indicators of attacks and unauthorized local/network/remote connections; identify unauthorized use using organization\u2011defined techniques; deploy monitoring capabilities strategically and ad hoc to collect essential information; analyze detected events/anomalies; adjust monitoring when risk changes; obtain legal opinion on monitoring activities; and provide system monitoring information to designated personnel or roles as needed or at defined frequencies [si-4].\n\n- User notification of monitoring: Display a system use notification/banner prior to granting access that informs users the system is a U.S. Government system, that usage may be monitored/recorded/audited, that unauthorized use is prohibited, and that use indicates consent to monitoring; retain the banner until users acknowledge and take explicit logon actions; and for public systems display appropriate system\u2011use information and authorized\u2011use descriptions consistent with privacy accommodations [ac-8].\n\nIf you need, I can map these controls into draft policy statements or a checklist for operational implementation.", "latency_ms": 6049.5, "document_count": 5, "citations": ["au-2", "au-14", "ma-4.1", "si-4", "ac-8"], "is_fallback": false}
